      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I had to meditate a little on the fact that William Maxwell's books have not made the best-seller lists.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I had to meditate a little on the fact that William Maxwell's books have not made the best-seller lists.</p>
        <p>I don't suppose there's a list of the works that seldom if ever make it to the used-book sale tables, because their owners don't want to let go of them. I think Mr. Maxwell's books would make it to that list. I'm not selling my copies.</p>
        <p>Another list I think his works would lead would be a list of the books whose images stay with you, haunting you the rest of your life. I find I can hardly think of things French without images from "The Chateau" drifting by; those images always make me feel tender toward France and its people, and grateful to William Maxwell. DORIS BUCHER  Atlanta</p>
      </block>
